<DOC><DOCNO> AP880401-0100 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1114EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Rebels     04-01 0173</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Philippines-Rebels,0177</SECOND><HEAD>Four Rebels, Two Soldiers Killed In Clash</HEAD><DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Communist rebels and soldiers foughta four-hour battle that left four rebels and two soldiers dead, thegovernment-owned news agency reported today.   The Philippine News Agency said three other rebels were woundedand captured during the battle Thursday near the town of Guagua,about 40 miles northeast of Manila. Two other soldiers were wounded.   The encounter began around noon when some 30 New People's Armyguerrillas opened fire on a government patrol sent to verifyreports that rebels had been sighted in the area, the agency said.   On Wednesday, security forces captured seven top communistleaders in raids on two rebel hideouts in suburban Manila. Thosearrested included Romulo Kintanar, the alleged guerrilla commander;Rafael Baylosis, secretary general of the Communist Party of thePhilippines; and Central Committee member Benjamin de Vera.   President Corazon Aquino hailed the arrests as a major victoryand said it showed her government had turned the tide against therebels in their 19-year insurgency.</TEXT></DOC>